\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\line }{\f0\fs24\b0 As she reached more and more permanent mastery of her isolation, she came to realize that the self she sought lay \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93beyond\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93beneath\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93behind\u8221\'94 (to use her own expressions) the world of her psychophysical actions and reactions. Out of reach of the endless rhythm of responses, of recordings on her memory, of the fast-paced hip chatter of her companions, of blaring monologues by individuals. She became slowly more sensitive and expectant that she would find the self she sought, wrapped in semitransparent shadows. It was independent, she believed, of that distracting outer world, and of her inner psychic theater which was always at the mercy of that outer world and was so easily shattered by it. The restlessness of details had no place with the self. She came to believe that, if she could prevent the \u8220\'93bad flow\u8221\'94 of others entering, she could achieve \u8220\'93perfection of personhood.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The source was not the subconscious, not a sixth sense or telepathy or any of those gimmicky tags,\u8221\'94 as she puts it. The source, she thought, was the self in each one. She said: \u8220\'93The self has a means of communication which does not need images or thoughts or logic or any particle of matter.\u8221\'94 Psychologists and physiologists, she knew, identified the self with brain circuitry and synaptic joints and the mechanisms of sensation. This was like saying that the violin was the source of the violinist\u8217\'92s music. Religionists and spiritualists identified the self with \u8220\'93soul\u8221\'94 or \u8220\'93spirit\u8221\'94\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 even with God, or a god. And both psychologists and religionists insisted you make choices. And so, in most people, that source and its \u8220\'93flow\u8221\'94 were split into a kind of \u8220\'93black-and-white\u8221\'94 condition. Most people were always choosing, responding, being responsible for their actions, saying yes or no, and thereby \u8220\'93fissioning the self\u8217\'92s lively unity.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Marianne no longer saw or felt any sensation of sunlight or wind. The outer world had become a flat and painted picture neither fresh nor hot nor cold. And the movements of people and animals and objects were angular tracings with no depth and no coherent sound. All meaning was drained from the scene.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The only movement was within her. Bit by bit \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93the net, now like a sharp, all-surrounding hand, tightened, narrowing and narrowing all my consciousness.\u8221\'94 At every moment, under that pressure, she was \u8220\'93opening up every secret part of my self, saying, \u8216\'91Yes,\u8217\'92 \u8216\'91Yes,\u8217\'92 \u8216\'91Yes,\u8217\'92 to a power that would not take \u8216\'91No\u8217\'92 for an answer.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 And none who saw her, a young girl sprawled motionless on the bench in the sunlight, could guess that Marianne was becoming a casement of possession.}
